.TH KIRO-REPORT 8 "2026-06-01" "Kiro" "Kiro System Tools"
.SH NAME
kiro-report \- generate a public-safe Kiro diagnostic report for Kiro Discussions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kiro-report
[\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR]
[\fB\-v\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR]
[\fB\-o\fR|\fB\-\-output\fR \fIPATH\fR]
[\fB\-c\fR|\fB\-\-copy\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kiro-report
produces a single log file a user can paste into the Kiro Discussions board
when asking for help. It reuses the full
.BR kiro-diag (8)
snapshot, adds the dynamic failure evidence a maintainer needs to debug, then
.B redacts
every system-identifying value before writing the file, so it is safe to share
on a public board.
.PP
The report contains:
.IP \(bu 4
The complete
.BR kiro-diag (8)
snapshot (hardware, GPU, kernel, desktop, network, ...)
.IP \(bu 4
Graphics driver packages with versions: Xorg
.I xf86-video-*
and
.IR xf86-input-* ,
Mesa, Vulkan, VA-API/VDPAU, NVIDIA
.IP \(bu 4
The full list of explicitly-installed packages
.RI ( pacman\ -Qe )
.IP \(bu 4
Failed systemd units
.IP \(bu 4
Journal errors of this boot (priority err and above)
.IP \(bu 4
Kernel ring-buffer errors
.RI ( dmesg )
.IP \(bu 4
Recent pacman transactions from
.I /var/log/pacman.log
.IP \(bu 4
The Calamares install log
.RI ( /var/log/Calamares.log ),
when present
.SH REDACTION
Before the file is written, the following are replaced with placeholders:
IPv4/IPv6 addresses, MAC addresses, UUIDs, the systemd machine-id, the
hostname, and the current username (including
.IR /home/<user> ).
Automated scrubbing is never perfect \(em review the file once before posting.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a help message and exit (does not require root).
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Print version information and exit (does not require root).
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output " " \fIPATH\fR
Write the report to
.I PATH
instead of the default
.IR ~/kiro-report-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS.log .
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-copy
Also copy the report to the clipboard, wrapped in a Markdown
.RB ( ``` )
code fence so it pastes straight into a Discussions code block. The session
clipboard is reached as the invoking user; needs
.B wl-copy
on Wayland or
.B xclip
/
.B xsel
on X11, and a running graphical session.
.SH NOTES
Must be run as root (it re-runs itself via polkit/sudo as needed):
.B sudo kiro-report
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR kiro-diag (8),
.BR kiro-audit (8),
.BR kiro-verify (8)
